{"name": "Fullscript", "size": "\r\n                                    501-1k employees\r\n                                ", "status": "\r\n                                    Private\r\n                                ", "industry": "\r\n                            Computer Software, eCommerce, Health Care\r\n                        ", "founded": "\r\n                                    2012\r\n                                ", "locations": ["245 Cooper Street, Ottawa Canada", "9185 E Pima Center Pkwy STE 200, Scottsdale, AZ"], "company_technologies": ["kubernetes", "rails", "ruby", "react", "graphql", "javascript", "typescript", "apollo", "php", "sql", "python", "wordpress", "go", "golang"], "about_company": ["\r\n                        ", "\u00a0is written with Ruby on Rails, and our product is built on our internal GraphQL API. On the front-end, we\u2019re using React, TypeScript, and Apollo to create top-notch experiences for our users. If you are a Full-Stack Developer, you\u2019ll have the chance to work across the whole stack.", "Our team cares about doing things well, and about the developer experience on the team. We host in-house training on all sorts of topics, from React all the way through to Kubernetes. Fullscript is a place where you\u2019ll be encouraged to learn, mentor, and grow.", "Check out our culture guide here: https://fullscript.com/culture", "\u201cCan\u2019t say enough great things about the work environment here. Great people and interesting problems to solve. This is my first job working with Ruby and I\u2019ve got to say I really enjoy the language. It\u2019s very developer friendly and lets you do some cool stuff! The rest of the tech stack is very modern and sensibly chosen. We have a well maintained react codebase and people are passionate about keeping it healthy and easy to work in.\"", "- ", "\u201cDuring my first week at Fullscript as a first time developer, I got to write code that was pushed to production immediately. This gave me a huge sense of ownership, which is a core value of the engineering team here. Our primary Front End stack includes React, TypeScript, and Emotion. I love working at a mission driven company where everyone is encouraged to make their own impact.\u201d", "- ", "\"We style our components with emotion and we test with enzyme and jest. We have a new and very modern application and there is almost no legacy application to maintain (most code in the frontend has been written in the last 3 years). We stay on latest and greatest versions of our libraries, and we are always looking at ways to improve our patterns.\u00a0We have a dedicated team that owns UI components and infrastructure (also Server Side Rendering (SSR)), but we are all encouraged and participate in improving our component library and tooling.", "We have different kinds of frontend developers, some css/style/design focused, others prefer to focus more on javascript/graphql/apollo, some lean more towards full stack and like to spend time working on Ruby. We all come together to build Fullscript and it's a great thing to see such diversity in knowledge and expertises work together to achieve one common goal.", "The developer experience is the best I've ever seen or even heard of. Our DevOps team is top notch and are an example of BEST BEST practices in the industry. We release to production every 30 minutes. Something goes wrong, your build is not passing, your test environment is not running, your code that went out needs reverting, they are there and responding within seconds - they've got you always. The tooling for developers is maintained by the DevOps team and you will never have it this easy. First day at work you will be able to setup your entire development environment in minutes, and hit the ground running. You will be able to focus on your code, what you build, and how to build it better. Not debugging constant problems with your dev environment or your computer.\"", "-", "\"Fullscript\u2019s core app is a robust Ruby on Rails monolith that uses React for the front-end. We have an in-house development toolkit that allows engineers to setup their development environment in mere moments and complete complex actions with easy to remember aliases. I love working at Fullscript for the amazing culture we have, the colleagues I work with everyday, and the quality we put into everything we develop. I\u2019ve learned a lot from our patterns and conventions, and now I\u2019m giving back by writing great code which is very exciting for me.\"", "-\u00a0", "\"I love working at Fullscript. Working here is a continual joy: everyone is rooting for you and your success. There's so much investment made into you and your growth. I would not be the developer I am today if I hadn't had the support, encouragement, and opportunities I was given here. I've learned so much from everyone around me, and I know I've made an impact on them as well. The care we have for one another is apparent in the shoutouts, DMs, and intense investment we all have in our culture and relationships with each other. I'm so grateful to work with such a wonderful team of people every day.", "There's so much opportunity for learning new things, and if you so desire, you're able to collaborate with other teams on projects that are outside of your normal domain (what we call 10% projects). My team in specific has been working with classic MVC rails with sprinkles of javascript (added via stimulusJS), and it's been a blast so far. In particular, I love that we're encouraged to bring up and help fix things that aren't working. Whether that be tech related, process related, bug fixes, or otherwise.\"", "-", "\"One of the main reasons why I love working at Fullscript is the tech stack that we use. It's modern, flexible and allows us to build awesome features\u00a0easily. Another reason is that we're not afraid of change. If there are better tools/libraries for the job, we take the time to try them out. The\u00a0best part - it's a good place to live. I feel comfortable in our tech stack. It's clean, easy to change and allows us to do what we do best.\"", "\u00a0"], "people": ["https://stackoverflow.com/users/1007409/kurt-funai?tab=profile", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/story/3799405", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10141077/chantal?tab=profile", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/74897/ffoeg?tab=profile", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10141217/josh-robertson?tab=profile", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1279940/hossam-mourad?tab=profile", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/story/2158047", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/12543036/david-ma?tab=profile", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10348488/marco-antonio-espinoza-navarro?tab=profile", "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5255445/andymo?tab=profile"], "jobs_openings": ["560618", "560617", "559683", "555260", "558897"]}
